				<span class="postdetails">
					<br /><b>Joined:</b> Sat Feb 12, 2005 9:43 pm<br /><b>Posts:</b> 5251<br /><b>Location:</b> Rio de Janeiro - Brazil
				</span>

			</td>
			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">65024U wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Oh, yes. I will test in other emulators. I have FCEUX im testing in, works the same. Easier to load roms so im going to use that more often now....I hope it isn't making a DEB file like others complained, I haven't checked....</div><br />FCEUX only creates these files when you use its debugger. If you don't use the debugger, you don't have to worry. The bebugger IS pretty neat though, so I suggest you check it out. There will be times when looking at the static code won't be enough to find bugs, and you will need a debugger for sure.<br /><br />But don't forget about the two emulators I mentioned. I'm sure you know that no emulator behaves exactly like the real console, right? For this reason, some emulators will forgive errors that the real hardware wouldn't, and you end up with a "Nesticle game" (there are a lot of those, made before it was easy to test on real hardware) rather than a "NES game". Currently, Nintendulator and Nestopia are as close as it gets to a real NES, so be sure to try your code on them, and on a real NES if you can.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Is there a depository of games here that everyone's put together? I'd LOVE to try some!</div>
<br />Believe it or not, we don't finish a lot of games here! Most of us are too ambitious with our personal projects, and spend years and years working on our dream games. Some just give up, others slow down, and so far nothing groundbreaking has been released.
<br />
<br />There are a few games released, mostly single-screen puzzle games, which I happen to hate, but so far it seems like the only way to get something done, picking a simple project. The only person I've seen that successfully broke the cycle of simple puzzle games was Sivak, with his game Battle Kid. It's not free though, you have to buy the cart.
<br />
<br />I hope that from now on more and more people will break free from the puzzle game stereotype, and that we get lots of new games that show improvements over Battle Kid, just as it was an improvement over puzzle games.
<br />
<br />I'll let others link you to the few finished games they consider relevant, since like I said I don't care much for simplistic games.</div>

