				</span>

			</td>
			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">65024U wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Atleast it isn't a puzzle game!</div><br /><img src="./images/smilies/icon_lol.gif" alt=":lol:" title="Laughing" /> IMO, Pong is already better, because it's action-based, as opposed to turn-based, so it's a step closer to the awesome action games everybody would like to make/play.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Because I am guessing you have to go through the PPU because the 2A03 isn't hooked to the same RAM?</div><br />Exactly. There's CPU memory and PPU memory, and there is no direct way for one to access the memory of the other. For communications, the PPU offers 2 ports, an address port (accessed through CPU address $2006) and a data port ($2007). Every time you have to write to or read from PPU memory you have to use those ports, there is no other way.<br /><br />Also, you can only do it while the PPU is not rendering images, otherwise you'd screw up its rendering process and the display would get all corrupt. The PPU is considered free for memory access when both sprites and background are disabled or during VBlank. Those are the only times you can write to and read from VRAM.<br /><br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Im gona maybe need help later for PPU sprite overlap, that seems confusing and like I will need it.....</div>
<br />What do you mean sprite overlap? Is it to use more than 3 colors? If so, there is no trick, just arrange your sprites in a way that they complete each other to form the bigger graphic. Sprites with higher priority will stay on top of the ones with lower priority, but if you "cut holes" in the high priority sprites so that the low priority ones are visible you don't even have to worry about priority.</div>

